  "title": "Preference Learning from Physics-Based Feedback: Tuning Language Models to Design BCC/B2 Superalloys",
  "experiments_summary": "The study applies a two-stage training pipeline to three open-weight language models (LLaMA-3.1-8B, Gemma-2-9B, OLMo-2-7B) for BCC/B2 superalloy design. First, supervised fine-tuning (SFT) is performed using 54,648 training examples consisting of (BCC composition, B2 composition, B2 volume %) triples derived from 207 known BCC and 88 known B2 compositions from the Materials Project. Models are trained with LoRA adapters (rank=8, α=32) using causal language modeling. Second, 5,000 candidates are sampled from each SFT model and evaluated using Thermo-Calc thermodynamic simulations across temperatures from 373K to 2273K. A hierarchical reward function is constructed based on four synthesis objectives: (1) BCC and B2 phase coexistence, (2) BCC forming first, (3) B2 existing at room temperature, and (4) <10% non-BCC/B2 phases, with lattice mismatch as a fine-grained quality metric. Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) is then applied using 125,000 preference pairs (top 25% generations paired with 100 randomly selected lower-ranked ones), with β=0.5 to prevent distribution shift. Baselines include random search, few-shot prompting of API models (GPT-4.1, GPT-O3, Gemini-2.5), prompt-tuned Gemini-2.5 using MIPROv2, agentic systems with generator-evaluator loops, and prior crystal generation models (Crystal-LLM, CDVAE). Evaluation metrics include compositional validity (Pauling electronegativity test), coverage (recall and precision via Euclidean distance in Matminer feature space), novelty (distance from existing Materials Project alloys), mean reward score, and unique pair generation rate. KL divergence analysis between SFT and DPO models is performed on generated tokens to diagnose model behavior, particularly for OLMo's performance degradation."
